The festive auspicious sign of the figure “8” – which in Chinese rhymes with the character for prosperity – and a Chinese character for auspiciousness are to be shown in scenes two and four. 
 
Other major fireworks displays in Hong Kong take place on July 1 – this year to celebrate the 20th anniversary of the city’s handover from UK to Chinese authorities – and October 1 for National Day. Another event is held on December 31. 
 
The Lunar New Year show comes a day after the city’s annual parade through Tsim Sha Tsui. Thousands of people lined the streets on Saturday night to watch nearly 3,000 performers from some 25 international and local performing groups.</TEXT> 
